00:07:10.667 --> 00:07:15.140
because I was like,
"Okay, how do I do this?"

00:07:15.140 --> 00:07:17.592
"I don't have a video
camera, should I go get one?"

00:07:17.592 --> 00:07:21.588
I was like, "No, because
that would cost money."

00:07:22.273 --> 00:07:24.814
With Nadia, we just had this screen going,

00:07:24.814 --> 00:07:28.007
so there must be some type of
software that captures a screen.

00:07:28.007 --> 00:07:30.952
I didn't even know there were
screen capture software existed.

00:07:30.952 --> 00:07:33.037
I did a web search, I found
some freeware that did it,

00:07:33.037 --> 00:07:35.242
and I needed an art program.

00:07:35.242 --> 00:07:39.562
I only used Microsoft Paint
for the first 500 videos

00:07:39.562 --> 00:07:43.010
and just started doing it and
when I put those first videos up,

00:07:43.010 --> 00:07:46.132
the first collection of
videos, 20 or 30 videos,

00:07:46.132 --> 00:07:48.343
my cousins literally did tell
me that they preferred me

00:07:48.343 --> 00:07:51.068
on YouTube than in person.

00:07:51.676 --> 00:07:53.477
I think there's a lot of things.

00:07:53.477 --> 00:07:55.677
Since then, I've heard a lot of feedback.

00:07:55.677 --> 00:07:56.777
One is just the form factor.

00:07:56.777 --> 00:07:58.278
This is true of any on-demand video.

00:07:58.278 --> 00:08:00.977
You can pause, you can
repeat, you can review stuff

00:08:00.977 --> 00:08:04.229
that you should've learned
last week or last year

00:08:04.229 --> 00:08:06.852
or a couple of years ago, you
don't have to feel embarrassed.

00:08:06.852 --> 00:08:08.489
You can do it when you're ready for it,

00:08:08.489 --> 00:08:12.447
you can go ahead, it's
not a one-size fits all,

00:08:12.447 --> 00:08:14.258
but that's true of all on-demand video.

00:08:14.258 --> 00:08:17.562
Khan Academy is not the
first on-demand video.

00:08:17.562 --> 00:08:20.614
MIT open courseware
started doing this in 2001.

00:08:20.614 --> 00:08:24.320
I'm sure there's people
who did it before that.

00:08:24.602 --> 00:08:26.831
I think the feedback I get
over and over again from people

00:08:26.831 --> 00:08:31.166
is that they appreciate
how conversational it is.

00:08:31.166 --> 00:08:33.621
To some degree, that wasn't by design.

00:08:33.621 --> 00:08:35.840
It was literally like I didn't
care, because it was for my cousins.

00:08:35.840 --> 00:08:37.371
They're not paying me, so I said,

00:08:37.371 --> 00:08:39.121
"Let me just make some videos for them."

00:08:39.121 --> 00:08:40.872
There's literally an early
video where I answered

00:08:40.872 --> 00:08:45.372
a telemarketer call during the
video and I don't edit it out.

00:08:45.372 --> 00:08:47.488
It's just there, I'm like, "I'm
not interested in Dish Network.

00:08:47.488 --> 00:08:52.599
"Please stop bothering
me," and I (laughter).

00:08:52.599 --> 00:09:00.404
(unintelligible) Exactly, how to
say no to obnoxious telemarketers.

00:09:00.404 --> 00:09:03.321
People enjoy the conversational nature.

00:09:03.321 --> 00:09:05.236
Early on, because these
are for my cousins,

00:09:05.236 --> 00:09:08.780
I didn't have a script, I
didn't have a lesson plan even.

00:09:08.780 --> 00:09:10.115
Some of those early videos, actually,
I kind of cringe at them now,

00:09:10.115 --> 00:09:13.534
because I'm like, "Hmm, what
should I talk about now?"

00:09:13.534 --> 00:09:16.952
and I just do, "Let's talk about this."

00:09:16.952 --> 00:09:20.661
People really like the idea
that I'm expressing exactly

00:09:20.661 --> 00:09:22.835
what's going on in my brain right now.

00:09:22.835 --> 00:09:25.131
It's not some thing that's
made by some bureaucracy

00:09:25.131 --> 00:09:30.100
to meet some state standard and
one group of people write a script

00:09:30.100 --> 00:09:31.795
with some computer graphics and
then another group of people

00:09:31.795 --> 00:09:35.320
just read the script while
the computer graphics happen.

00:09:35.320 --> 00:09:37.325
They like the organic nature.

00:09:37.325 --> 00:09:39.867
A lot of people, once
again, the form factor

00:09:39.867 --> 00:09:45.991
that's kind of our brand now,
I did it because I didn't want

00:09:45.991 --> 00:09:48.659
to have a video camera, but people
say it actually feels intimate,

00:09:48.659 --> 00:09:51.742
it actually feels like you and
I are sitting next to each other

00:09:51.742 --> 00:09:55.117
and looking through the concept together.

00:09:55.117 --> 00:09:56.159
This is kind of crazy.

00:09:56.159 --> 00:09:57.242
I've gotten letters
from people who've said,

00:09:57.242 --> 00:09:59.760
"Not only does it feel
like I'm next to you,

00:09:59.760 --> 00:10:02.742
"it feels like you're in my brain."

00:10:02.742 --> 00:10:05.324
When they go normally,
on an everyday basis,

00:10:05.324 --> 00:10:07.743
when they go and think they
think in their own voice,

00:10:07.743 --> 00:10:10.464
but as soon as they get to a math
test, all of sudden they say,

00:10:10.464 --> 00:10:16.832
"Well, let's see what the next
-" and they hear me. (laughter)

00:10:16.832 --> 00:10:20.332
The other thing is, it had
to be limited to ten minutes.

00:10:20.332 --> 00:10:22.270
I guess that was another
Khan Academy innovation,

00:10:22.270 --> 00:10:26.140
but once again, YouTube
limited to ten minutes,

00:10:26.140 --> 00:10:29.585
so I had to do it and that
was really good discipline

00:10:29.585 --> 00:10:32.517
and now I've gotten tons of feedback

00:10:32.517 --> 00:10:33.998
and I've actually dug up research

00:10:33.998 --> 00:10:35.787
that shows people actually
can't pay attention

00:10:35.787 --> 00:10:39.537
in any reasonable way for
more than 10 to 18 minutes.

00:10:39.537 --> 00:10:41.749
After they do, they zone
our for five minutes.

00:10:41.749 --> 00:10:44.363
After zoning out for five minutes,
they realize they were zoning out.

00:10:44.363 --> 00:10:46.462
They say, "Oh my God,
let me pay attention,"

00:10:46.462 --> 00:10:48.330
