like who was more than one
standard deviation behind

00:11:54.364 --> 00:11:56.534
four days into the camp, and now is more

00:11:56.534 --> 00:11:59.565
than one standard deviation
above the class average

00:11:59.565 --> 00:12:02.981
at the end of the camp and
there was this one girl.

00:12:02.981 --> 00:12:05.313
I won't mention the name for privacy,

00:12:05.313 --> 00:12:07.566
but I talked to her later and
literally, she just had to get

00:12:07.566 --> 00:12:10.398
positive and negative numbers,
adding and subtracting them

00:12:10.398 --> 00:12:12.813
out of the way and after she
did that, she just raced ahead

00:12:12.813 --> 00:12:14.422
and we started looking
for it more and more.

00:12:14.422 --> 00:12:15.899
There's other things we found.

00:12:15.899 --> 00:12:18.124
Not only that, which is a big
deal, the kid that otherwise,

00:12:18.124 --> 00:12:20.648
would have been tracked as a
slow students is now showing

00:12:20.648 --> 00:12:24.096
that if they just had the
chance to really digest

00:12:24.096 --> 00:12:26.315
the information properly,
if you think about it,

00:12:26.315 --> 00:12:29.230
that's actually a property of someone
who is probably innately gifted,

00:12:29.230 --> 00:12:31.065
is someone who really wants
to digest something properly,

00:12:31.065 --> 00:12:33.316
not just understand the
mechanics and probably

00:12:33.316 --> 00:12:35.563
some of those people are
being left behind right now.

00:12:35.563 --> 00:12:38.813
It allows them to race ahead,
but the other interesting thing,

00:12:38.813 --> 00:12:44.231
we've seen this in Los Altos, is there
are some classically rock star students,

00:12:44.231 --> 00:12:47.680
the ones that are always straight
A, they're really competitive,

00:12:47.680 --> 00:12:50.041
when you force them to
start at the beginning,

00:12:50.041 --> 00:12:52.347
from the most basic
concepts, even some of them

00:12:52.347 --> 00:12:55.233
start to stumble at things that
they really should have learned

00:12:55.233 --> 00:12:58.308
in third or fourth grade and what
they've probably done since then

00:12:58.308 --> 00:13:01.306
is just they've been very good at
pretending around their deficiencies

00:13:01.306 --> 00:13:05.877
or getting around them and so
almost everyone has these gaps.

00:13:05.877 --> 00:13:09.418
That same summer program where
that first student was at,

00:13:09.418 --> 00:13:11.505
one thing we saw over and over again,

00:13:11.505 --> 00:13:14.145
there was actually two groups.

00:13:14.145 --> 00:13:15.900
This was seventh graders.

00:13:15.900 --> 00:13:17.794
In one group, the teacher said,
"Oh no, this would be silly

00:13:17.794 --> 00:13:20.363
"to make my seventh
graders start at 1+1=2,"

00:13:20.363 --> 00:13:22.552
so we started all of
them at sixth grade math.

00:13:22.552 --> 00:13:24.336
The other group, we're like,
"Yeah, let's just start them off

00:13:24.336 --> 00:13:28.772
"at 1+1=2," and we saw the group
that didn't have the chance

00:13:28.772 --> 00:13:32.412
to remediate, they just
hit a wall at some point.

00:13:32.412 --> 00:13:34.690
They just couldn't progress,
or some subset of them

00:13:34.690 --> 00:13:37.051
couldn't progress at some point,
while the group that started

00:13:37.051 --> 00:13:41.495
at 1+1=2, one, it was surprising
how many really basic weaknesses

00:13:41.495 --> 00:13:43.275
some of these seventh graders had.

00:13:43.275 --> 00:13:45.454
Literally, adding two-digit
numbers, knowing how to regroup

00:13:45.454 --> 00:13:48.705
or carry or things like this,
but once they got through that,

00:13:48.705 --> 00:13:51.204
just as a group, they way
outperformed the other group.

00:13:51.204 --> 00:13:53.955
Even their worst performers were better

00:13:53.955 --> 00:13:55.686
than the best performers
in the other group,

00:13:55.686 --> 00:13:59.357
which is a narrative that I
think we've been observing.

00:13:59.357 --> 00:14:02.038
No matter what you do, you get the
best algebra teacher in the room,

00:14:02.038 --> 00:14:04.954
you have an innately gifted kid,
no matter how hard the kid works,

00:14:04.954 --> 00:14:07.788
if that kid has trouble
with third grade math,

00:14:07.788 --> 00:14:13.507
there's really no way that you can
do it in a standard education model.

00:14:13.539 --> 00:14:15.072
Jeff: Speaking of
standard education models,

00:14:15.072 --> 00:14:17.538
talk a little bit about
the software platform

00:14:17.538 --> 00:14:21.288
you guys have been developing,
the success you've had,

00:14:21.288 --> 00:14:24.372
in terms of working with Los
Altos as a school district,

00:14:24.372 --> 00:14:28.622
and the impact that the
videos plus the software

00:14:28.622 --> 00:14:31.205
in the classroom is having
on classroom dynamics.

00:14:31.205 --> 00:14:34.758
Sal: Yeah, the software,
I've hinted at it.

00:14:34.758 --> 00:14:36.998
If you saw the TED talk you
kind of know what it is,

00:14:36.998 --> 00:14:40.789
but it's actually stuff that I started
working on before the first video.

00:14:40.789 --> 00:14:44.705
A few months into working
with Nadia and her brothers,

00:14:44.705 --> 00:14:46.951
I would point them to random websites.

00:14:46.951 --> 00:14:49.051
I was like, "Hey, there's a site
that has a couple of cool problems.

00:14:49.051 --> 00:14:51.651
"Why don't you work on those,"
or, "Here's another site,"

00:14:51.651 --> 00:14:53.534
and the next morning
I'd have no information

00:14:53.534 --> 00:14:56.262
of what they did, I didn't
believe them that they said

00:14:56.262 --> 00:14:58.670
they did the problem or how
many they got right or wrong.

00:14:58.670 --> 00:15:02.409
I started writing this little
javascript problem generator

00:15:02.409 --> 00:15:03.742
and I was really just trying
to make sure that they had

00:15:03.742 --> 00:15:06.529
the core skill down, that they
really just understood the core skill

00:15:06.529 --> 00:15:07.910
and I put a little database
behind it so I could see

00:15:07.910 --> 00:15:10.470
when did they do the problem,
did they use the hints,

00:15:10.470 --> 00:15:12.884
and whatever else.

00:15:12.884 --> 00:15:14.466
Then over time I had a
bunch of these modules

00:15:14.466 --> 00:15:17.480
and I got tired of assigning, "Oh
now you're ready for this module,"

00:15:17.480 --> 00:15:18.679
So I said, "Hey, if you get
ten in a row on this module

00:15:18.679 --> 00:15:20.716
"it'll automatically
assign you to the next,"

00:15:20.716 --> 00:15:22.466
and that's where the whole knowledge tree,

00:15:22.466 --> 00:15:24.784
if you saw the TED talk, came about.

00:15:24.784 --> 00:15:25.574
It was originally something for me.

00:15:25.574 --> 00:15:27.067
It was a tool for myself to
understand all the modules I'd built

00:15:27.067 --> 00:15:29.865
and the dependencies and then I said,

00:15:29.865 --> 00:15:31.732
"Well, it'd be cool for
a student to see it,"

00:15:31.732 --> 00:15:33.535
and once I did my cousins loved that.

00:15:33.535 --> 00:15:34.686
It was like Legend of
Zelda all of a sudden.

00:15:34.686 --> 00:15:39.014
They could see, "Hey, I could get
over there," and all the rest.

00:15:39.807 --> 00:15:41.939
Fast forward, the summer
camp started using it.

00:15:41.939 --> 00:15:44.988
Even there, we said, "Hey, every
kid can now work at their own pace.

00:15:44.988 --> 00:15:48.061
"The tools, the videos are there and
now the teacher can just intervene

00:15:48.061 --> 00:15:51.268
"when someone's stuck,"
and then you fast forward

00:15:51.268 --> 00:15:56.024
to November of 2010, Los Altos
school board literally just met

00:15:56.024 --> 00:15:58.026
with myself and Shantanu,
who's our president,

00:15:58.026 --> 00:16:01.144
and said, "We've heard great
things about what you're doing.

00:16:01.144 --> 00:16:02.195
"We want to learn more about
it and what would you do

00:16:02.195 --> 00:16:05.312
"if you had just whatever you wanted
to do with the math classroom?"

00:16:05.312 --> 00:16:08.813
and we said we'd have every
student work at their own pace,

00:16:08.813 --> 00:16:10.645
the role of the teacher,
they won't have to lecture,

00:16:10.645 --> 00:16:12.979
they won't have to grade papers.

00:16:12.979 --> 00:16:16.730
I don't want to say just, but
they will walk into a room

00:16:16.730 --> 00:16:18.979
and they'll get a dashboard and
the dashboard will tell them

00:16:18.979 --> 00:16:23.311
where every student is
working, who's stuck on what.

00:16:23.311 --> 00:16:26.978
If they want to dive deeper they
can press a couple of clicks

00:16:26.978 --> 00:16:28.861
and they can see exactly what
a student's been working on

00:16:28.861 --> 00:16:31.812
and really diagnose what's
probably wrong with the student

00:16:31.812 --> 00:16:33.758
and then use that information to either do

00:16:33.758 --> 00:16:36.340
a very focused intervention themselves

00:16:36.340 --> 00:16:39.115
or get some of the student's
peers to do an intervention.

00:16:39.115 --> 00:16:40.334
What it does is it does a couple things.

00:16:40.334 --> 00:16:42.835
One, now everyone can
work at their own pace,

00:16:42.835 --> 00:16:45.503
the teacher's time is fully
leveraged and it's focused,

00:16:45.503 --> 00:16:48.808
and really just narrowing in
on exactly what the weak points

00:16:48.808 --> 00:16:52.976
for the students are, and the
third thing is probably not obvious

00:16:52.976 --> 00:16:56.149
from the TED talk and if we've had
critics that's in this third area,

00:16:56.149 --> 00:16:58.534
it's that, "Okay, yeah
Khan Academy, the videos,

00:16:58.534 --> 00:17:01.124
"that's probably really
good for basic skills,

00:17:01.124 --> 00:17:03.124
"and even the videos it's good
for conceptual development,

00:17:03.124 --> 00:17:04.914
"but what about project-based learning?"

00:17:04.914 --> 00:17:07.395
There's this whole school of
thought of constructivist learning

00:17:07.395 --> 00:17:09.831
and it's always these math wars.

00:17:09.831 --> 00:17:10.914
There's always been this argument

00:17:10.914 --> 00:17:13.936
between the tiger mom school of learning

00:17:13.936 --> 00:17:17.342
and the constructivist Seymour
Papert play with Legos enough

00:17:17.342 --> 00:17:22.742
and eventually you'll
know calculus. (laughter)

00:17:22.742 --> 00:17:25.350
It's been like a war, right?

00:17:26.648 --> 00:17:28.770
People, the first time
they see Khan Academy,

00:17:28.770 --> 00:17:30.589
they think we are the tiger mom version,

00:17:30.589 --> 00:17:34.552
because it's like core
skills, it's lecture.

00:17:34.552 --> 00:17:37.014
The other thing I think really
differentiates our lectures over others

00:17:37.014 --> 00:17:38.488
and this was actually a surprise for me,

00:17:38.488 --> 00:17:42.598
is I made my lectures geared
towards someone like myself

00:17:42.598 --> 00:17:44.680
when I was 12 years old or 13.

00:17:44.680 --> 00:17:47.931
I wanted the rationale, I wanted
the conceptual development.

00:17:47.931 --> 00:17:49.515
I wanted my cousins to have that.

00:17:49.515 --> 00:17:52.403
I wanted them to really
innately understand math.

00:17:52.403 --> 00:17:55.181
I didn't think early on
that that would be popular.

00:17:55.181 --> 00:17:57.573
I thought that most students
would want the formulas.

00:17:57.573 --> 00:18:00.098
Most students wouldn't want
to think about the intuition.

00:18:00.098 --> 00:18:02.413
The surprising thing is over
and over again we get feedback

00:18:02.413 --> 00:18:05.431
from the students you
wouldn't normally associate

00:18:05.431 --> 00:18:06.841
with students liking math saying,

00:18:06.841 --> 00:18:09.789
"I'm angry that my teacher did
not introduce the intuition.

00:18:09.789 --> 00:18:11.109
"Now it's easy."

00:18:11.109 --> 00:18:14.765
Over and over again we get that,
but what we're in this debate

00:18:14.765 --> 00:18:18.395
between what's derisively
called the drill and kill

00:18:18.395 --> 00:18:20.232
and the constructivists,
what we're saying is,

00:18:20.232 --> 00:18:22.634
"No, it's not an either
or proposition now."

00:18:22.634 --> 00:18:24.182
What's happening in those
Los Altos classrooms

00:18:24.182 --> 00:18:27.206
are so much of the blocking and
tackling is being taken off,

00:18:27.206 --> 00:18:30.431
one, from the class time and
from the teacher's shoulders,

00:18:30.431 --> 00:18:33.811
that the teacher not only can
dive in and do very focused

00:18:33.811 --> 00:18:36.431
and meaningful interventions,
but all of this class time

00:18:36.431 --> 00:18:40.385
is freed up to do these
investigations, to do these projects.

00:18:40.385 --> 00:18:43.014
I'll challenge any classroom out there

00:18:43.014 --> 00:18:45.931
to see if they can do more project-based
learning and investigations

00:18:45.931 --> 00:18:48.058
than these Los Altos classes are doing

00:18:48.058 --> 00:18:49.626
and I would challenge
any classroom out there

00:18:49.626 --> 00:18:51.729
to see if they can do more
core skills development

00:18:51.729 --> 00:18:53.632
than these Los Altos classes are doing.

00:18:53.632 --> 00:18:56.017
It's kind of the best of both worlds.

00:18:56.017 --> 00:19:00.149
Jeff: One of my favorite parts of
your talk that I alluded to earlier

00:19:00.149 --> 00:19:03.033
was during Q and A with Bill Gates.

00:19:03.033 --> 00:19:06.368
At one point, everything that Sal
talks about sounds so extraordinary.

00:19:06.368 --> 00:19:08.450
It sounds like vision.

00:19:08.450 --> 00:19:11.699
How could it possibly be real,
how could we get so much good

00:19:11.699 --> 00:19:16.368
from one guy, a small team, a non-profit?

00:19:16.368 --> 00:19:18.253
At one point, Bill said,
"So, what would it take

00:19:18.253 --> 00:19:20.950
"to scale this to every
classroom in the country?

00:19:20.950 --> 00:19:22.534
"How long would that take?"

00:19:22.534 --> 00:19:23.726
Your response was -

00:19:23.726 --> 00:19:29.002
Sal: Yeah, technically, I'm giving little
asterisks now, by the way. (laughter)

00:19:29.002 --> 00:19:34.003
It can be adopted tomorrow
or now by every classroom.

00:19:34.003 --> 00:19:37.830
It's self-service, the dashboard's
everything, if a teacher goes.

00:19:37.830 --> 00:19:41.925
The realistic answer is there has
to be some type of deployment,

00:19:41.925 --> 00:19:44.035
but there's no reason why it doesn't,

00:19:44.035 --> 00:19:46.470
there's no fundamental barrier
for it being used tomorrow

00:19:46.470 --> 00:19:48.572
by every classroom in the world.

00:19:48.572 --> 00:19:50.420
Jeff: I think that's a
great jumping off point

00:19:50.420 --> 00:19:53.420
to open it up to the group here.

00:19:53.420 --> 00:19:55.256
We just want to do a
little brainstorming today.

00:19:55.256 --> 00:19:57.669
Sal's very interested in your
thoughts and I'd love to know

00:19:57.669 --> 00:20:00.088
how this group of people, how LinkedIn,

00:20:00.088 --> 00:20:02.386
how some of the folks who,
ultimately, may be viewing this

00:20:02.386 --> 00:20:05.670
can get involved, what help do you need?

00:20:05.670 --> 00:20:10.286
How can we start to dramatically
increase the footprint?

00:20:10.961 --> 00:20:11.974
Any questions or comments?

00:20:11.974 --> 00:20:14.335
Yeah, please.

00:20:17.512 --> 00:20:18.785
Audience Member: I didn't grow up here

00:20:18.785 --> 00:20:21.202
and I just saw your
TED talk a few days ago

00:20:21.202 --> 00:20:26.868
and after that I also saw the
TED talk that Ken Robinson gave

00:20:26.868 --> 00:20:29.926
about schools killing creativity.

00:20:29.926 --> 00:20:31.118
What are you thoughts about that

00:20:31.118 --> 00:20:34.596
and how has it influenced
what Khan Academy's doing

00:20:34.596 --> 00:20:37.892
and what it's planning to do?

00:20:37.892 --> 00:20:39.894
Sal: I think the Ken
Robinson talk's awesome

00:20:39.894 --> 00:20:43.894
and some people view our
talks as very aligned

00:20:43.894 --> 00:20:48.749
and some people have viewed it
that somehow they're not aligned.

00:20:48.749 --> 00:20:51.921
My point is going back to what's
going on in Los Altos classrooms

00:20:51.921 --> 00:20:54.289
is that right now, so much time is focused

00:20:54.289 --> 00:20:57.191
on the mandated curriculum from the state

00:20:57.191 --> 00:21:01.097
and so much time is focused on making sure

00:21:01.097 --> 00:21:05.402
that the worst don't do bad.

00:21:05.402 --> 00:21:09.402
There's no time for real creative work.

00:21:09.402 --> 00:21:12.799
I'd say even 95% of people
in classes right now

00:21:12.799 --> 00:21:15.522
that claim to do project-based learning

00:21:15.522 --> 00:21:17.523
or claim to do creative
things in the classroom,

00:21:17.523 --> 00:21:19.404
it's not creative, it's cookbook.

00:21:19.404 --> 00:21:22.857
It looks good, "Oh, we're
studying how we can send

00:21:22.857 --> 00:21:25.479
"a satellite to the moon," or
something, but they're not,

00:21:25.479 --> 00:21:30.608
it's some type of cookbook thing
with words in the right way.

00:21:30.608 --> 00:21:33.274
What we think and what I
hope Khan Academy enables

00:21:33.274 --> 00:21:35.359
and we'd like to pilot this
in more and more schools

00:21:35.359 --> 00:21:38.993
and it can enable a whole set of
really fundamentally creative things

00:21:38.993 --> 00:21:41.091
and some of that will
probably be on our platform.

00:21:41.091 --> 00:21:47.068
Actually, Jonathan, who used to
actually be a LinkedIn employee,

00:21:47.068 --> 00:21:48.503
for two summers we did a summer camp.

00:21:48.503 --> 00:21:53.411
We do this as R and D for what
is the future of real learning.

00:21:53.411 --> 00:21:56.867
You have this Khan Academy, the
videos, you can get a lot there,

00:21:56.867 --> 00:21:59.122
but if you really want people to
learn stuff and we did stuff with kids

00:21:59.122 --> 00:22:03.295
and this is stuff we might even
internalize into the software.

00:22:04.255 --> 00:22:06.021
It was pretty fun.

00:22:06.021 --> 00:22:07.522
It was all the games I wanted
to play with my friends

00:22:07.522 --> 00:22:11.090
at my birthday party, but
no one else wanted to.

00:22:11.090 --> 00:22:13.977
We literally would have
six kids playing Risk

00:22:13.977 --> 00:22:17.227
and we would have the other 24 kids,

00:22:17.227 --> 00:22:19.490
they would each get a
colored piece of cardboard

00:22:19.490 --> 00:22:25.610
that says, if you're holding
red at three o'clock,

00:22:25.610 --> 00:22:27.844
which is three hours from when we started,

00:22:27.844 --> 00:22:30.015
that colored piece of
cardboard would be worth

00:22:30.015 --> 00:22:33.395
the number of armies that
red army has at three o'clock

00:22:33.395 --> 00:22:35.560
and the same thing for
yellow and green and so on.

00:22:35.560 --> 00:22:37.919
We gave them $500 in Monopoly money each.

00:22:37.919 --> 00:22:41.289
They all started with one of
these and then we started the Risk

00:22:41.289 --> 00:22:47.094
and then we told the rest of the
24, "Trade the actual things."

00:22:47.094 --> 00:22:48.262
It was fascinating.

00:22:48.262 --> 00:22:50.767
We saw fifth graders start making models.

00:22:50.767 --> 00:22:52.895
There was one fifth grader who
started doing naked shorting

00:22:52.895 --> 00:22:55.436
without knowing what naked short -

00:22:55.436 --> 00:22:57.438
He would literally sell
something to someone,

00:22:57.438 --> 00:23:02.011
but say, "Wait, I'll give you the
actual security later." (laughter)

00:23:02.011 --> 00:23:04.060
Jeff: For those that don't know,
the financial derivative world,

00:23:04.060 --> 00:23:07.740
that had nothing to do with
the clothing (crosstalk).

00:23:07.740 --> 00:23:08.950
Sal: There was a little bit of that, too.

00:23:08.950 --> 00:23:12.643
No, no. (laughter)

00:23:12.643 --> 00:23:16.989
The summer camp would be shut
down if that was happening.

00:23:16.989 --> 00:23:18.322
It was fascinating.

00:23:18.322 --> 00:23:21.365
One kid came up to me and
he said how he figured out

00:23:21.365 --> 00:23:24.739
that right after someone's turn in Risk,

00:23:24.739 --> 00:23:28.040
their security went up,
because we've all played Risk,

00:23:28.040 --> 00:23:29.656
it looks like that person's
about to take over the world,

00:23:29.656 --> 00:23:34.739
but Risk has these huge swings, so
he didn't even look at the board.

00:23:34.739 --> 00:23:36.738
He just shorted whoever's turn it was

00:23:36.738 --> 00:23:42.266
and he ended up winning the
whole game, because he just -

00:23:42.266 --> 00:23:44.389
Then we played another time where
it was more of a determined,

00:23:44.389 --> 00:23:47.349
where we played a variation
called Paranoia Risk,

00:23:47.349 --> 00:23:49.797
where there's only one winner.

00:23:49.797 --> 00:23:51.963
Everyone's trying to eliminate
one person from the board.

00:23:51.963 --> 00:23:54.973
As soon as one person is
eliminated from the board,

00:23:54.973 --> 00:23:57.349
the person who was trying
to eliminate them, wins.

00:23:57.349 --> 00:24:01.516
Now, we said, "If you're
holding the color of the winner,

00:24:01.516 --> 00:24:04.050
"that's worth 100 and
everyone else is worth 0."

00:24:04.050 --> 00:24:05.357
Now it's pure probability.

00:24:05.357 --> 00:24:08.275
That security should trade,
if it's trading at $65,

00:24:08.275 --> 00:24:10.692
you're saying there's a 65% chance -

00:24:10.692 --> 00:24:12.099
I didn't tell them this ahead of time.

00:24:12.099 --> 00:24:13.193
It was amazing how many times

00:24:13.193 --> 00:24:15.943
the security started selling
for like $150 or $200.

00:24:15.943 --> 00:24:18.959
There was serious bubble
mentality going on.

00:24:18.959 --> 00:24:19.876
Anyway, I'm going on.

00:24:19.876 --> 00:24:23.375
I could talk for hours about this,
and we played Settlers of Catan,

00:24:23.375 --> 00:24:25.208
one time with separate board games.

00:24:25.208 --> 00:24:27.321
Then the second time around we
let them trade across countries

00:24:27.321 --> 00:24:29.366
and say, "Hey, how come we -

00:24:29.366 --> 00:24:30.968
We actually had a pariah
state that couldn't trade

00:24:30.968 --> 00:24:33.372
and we compared the development
to the ones that trade.

00:24:33.372 --> 00:24:35.305
Anyway, you get the general idea.

00:24:35.305 --> 00:24:38.089
There's a lot of stuff that can be
done, if class time is freed up,

00:24:38.089 --> 00:24:40.508
that's really deep, that
gives people understanding.

00:24:40.508 --> 00:24:44.092
In one round of the Risk,
I was the market maker

00:24:44.092 --> 00:24:46.116
and these students try to
find out (unintelligible)

00:24:46.116 --> 00:24:48.672
what a market maker is, what is a
secondary market versus a primary.

00:24:48.672 --> 00:24:49.621
All of this stuff.

00:24:49.621 --> 00:24:54.673
It might be relevant to you guys
very soon, I don't know. (laughter)

00:24:54.673 --> 00:24:58.227
My vision, to answer your
question, my vision is more of that

00:24:58.227 --> 00:25:00.463
without giving up the stuff that kids need

00:25:00.463 --> 00:25:03.590
to really prove to the world
on the SATs, the AP tests

00:25:03.590 --> 00:25:06.663
that they know those core skills, as well.

00:25:06.663 --> 00:25:08.361
Jeff: Sometimes people ask the question,

00:25:08.361 --> 00:25:10.409
What happens if some of
our best and brightest,

00:25:10.409 --> 00:25:13.693
rather than go into the financial
world and hedge fund trading,

00:25:13.693 --> 00:25:16.815
they were to go into areas like education?

00:25:16.815 --> 00:25:18.218
That's part of what happens.

00:25:18.218 --> 00:25:20.519
You get this brilliance
supplied in the right ways.

00:25:20.519 --> 00:25:21.863
Sal: There could be a good sequel to that,

00:25:21.863 --> 00:25:23.528
where there's a guy who's -

00:25:23.528 --> 00:25:25.827
I won't name any names, but he's a quant

00:25:25.827 --> 00:25:29.445
at a very prominent
hedge fund and he went -

00:25:29.445 --> 00:25:32.611
Pretty much, he left that fund
