00:30:19.622 --> 00:30:23.628
and how do you check out the code,
how do you see where all the ...

00:30:23.628 --> 00:30:25.512
There's even specs out
there for unbuilt modules

00:30:25.512 --> 00:30:28.045
if you don't have an
idea of what to build.

00:30:28.045 --> 00:30:29.154
They're all in javascript.

00:30:29.154 --> 00:30:31.214
They're pretty straightforward.

00:30:31.214 --> 00:30:33.687
Thinking about the learning is
probably harder than the programming.

00:30:33.687 --> 00:30:35.926
Jeff: Okay, Nick.

00:30:35.926 --> 00:30:37.661
Nick: Thanks for being here, first of all.

00:30:37.661 --> 00:30:40.878
My question is I've got two
kids and what I've learned

00:30:40.878 --> 00:30:42.666
in my experience with them is they have

00:30:42.666 --> 00:30:44.934
completely different ways of learning.

00:30:44.934 --> 00:30:47.798
Specifically, my son has
dyslexia, so for him,

00:30:47.798 --> 00:30:52.508
he's had to put a lot of energy
into doing well in school and so on.

00:30:52.508 --> 00:30:55.628
I wonder how the program accommodates kids

00:30:55.628 --> 00:30:59.183
who have learning challenges,
disabilities, and so on.

00:30:59.183 --> 00:31:03.518
Sal: This is, again, another
surprising thing that wasn't by design.

00:31:03.518 --> 00:31:05.422
When I started, I viewed
it as for my cousins,

00:31:05.422 --> 00:31:07.290
maybe catered to someone like myself,

00:31:07.290 --> 00:31:10.547
or probably a lot of you all, when
you all were 12 or 13 years old.

00:31:10.547 --> 00:31:14.296
Some of the biggest feedback
we get are from parents

00:31:14.296 --> 00:31:17.599
and students with learning disabilities.

00:31:17.599 --> 00:31:22.049
Dyslexia, ADHD, actually some parents

00:31:22.049 --> 00:31:25.086
of autistic students have
loved it and what it is,

00:31:25.086 --> 00:31:27.373
dyslexia, probably the main -

00:31:27.373 --> 00:31:30.524
One is the videos are
very, it's not just -

00:31:30.524 --> 00:31:33.165
I've been told this by
dyslexics, that just the fact

00:31:33.165 --> 00:31:36.623
that I'm writing it out, it's not
just printed text that just pops up,

00:31:36.623 --> 00:31:39.374
is a big deal, the fact that
I'm talking while I'm doing it,

00:31:39.374 --> 00:31:41.123
it helps integrate everything
and that's the same thing

00:31:41.123 --> 00:31:42.738
for people with ADHD.

00:31:42.738 --> 00:31:44.131
The fact that I'm using
these different colors

00:31:44.131 --> 00:31:46.440
for the different concepts.

00:31:46.440 --> 00:31:47.790
I think the biggest thing, and once again,

00:31:47.790 --> 00:31:49.584
this goes to the form factor,
is that it's self-paced.

00:31:49.584 --> 00:31:54.082
I think a lot of a dyslexic
student, they're stressed,

00:31:54.082 --> 00:31:55.518
and as soon as you're
stressed, you can't learn.

00:31:55.518 --> 00:31:57.419
That's the thing that most -

00:31:57.419 --> 00:32:00.188
There's stress if it's taking
you half a second longer

00:32:00.188 --> 00:32:04.194
to process something, but
you have this assembly line,

00:32:04.194 --> 00:32:06.195
move along at the same
pace, that's going to leave

00:32:06.195 --> 00:32:09.556
your son behind and now
there's none of that stress.

00:32:09.556 --> 00:32:13.628
He can take as much time as he
needs to digest the concept.

00:32:13.628 --> 00:32:16.058
Yeah, it's weird.

00:32:16.058 --> 00:32:17.793
I don't want it to seem like
this is a cure all for everyone,

00:32:17.793 --> 00:32:22.342
but we didn't design it, but
the gifted students love it,

00:32:22.342 --> 00:32:24.622
the students who are
falling behind love it,

00:32:24.622 --> 00:32:27.622
the adult learners, so it
is one of those things.

00:32:27.622 --> 00:32:29.350
If you just give people a chance to learn,

00:32:29.350 --> 00:32:32.930
you don't talk down to them,
you respect their intelligence,

00:32:32.930 --> 00:32:34.488
you don't just teach them formulas,

00:32:34.488 --> 00:32:38.289
and you give them instant
feedback, it's amazing,

00:32:38.289 --> 00:32:40.094
it kind of works for everybody.

00:32:40.094 --> 00:32:41.360
Nick: Thank you.

00:32:41.360 --> 00:32:45.198
Jeff: Sal, at root in all of
this, is a product that has proven

00:32:45.198 --> 00:32:47.834
to be incredibly effective
and you mentioned earlier,

00:32:47.834 --> 00:32:51.172
YouTube originally had limitations
on the duration of the video

00:32:51.172 --> 00:32:53.842
and that certainly contributed
to the form factor,

00:32:53.842 --> 00:32:56.728
but I'm assuming over time
there's been a lot of iteration.

00:32:56.728 --> 00:32:58.896
From a product development perspective,

00:32:58.896 --> 00:33:01.312
could you shed a little light on
the approach that you've taken,

00:33:01.312 --> 00:33:04.019
because you're doing something
very right, obviously and -

00:33:04.019 --> 00:33:07.477
Sal: Yeah, I've learned
now that there are words

00:33:07.477 --> 00:33:11.479
to describe our process, lean and
agile and all of this kind of stuff.

00:33:11.479 --> 00:33:16.187
It is literally just put stuff
out there and see what happens.

00:33:17.902 --> 00:33:19.433
There's that, that's kind
of the process, and I think,

00:33:19.433 --> 00:33:23.158
in terms of the actual
thing that goes out there,

00:33:23.158 --> 00:33:26.705
it's amazing how much money
and resources have been wasted

00:33:26.705 --> 00:33:29.210
on trying to make educational
materials that look polished,

00:33:29.210 --> 00:33:31.909
that look like this, and as soon as
you watch them you're disengaged.

00:33:31.909 --> 00:33:35.868
I think it's this focus on
the end user and nothing else

00:33:35.868 --> 00:33:41.119
and not trying to pretend when I
started and now as an organization,

00:33:41.119 --> 00:33:45.523
we never want to fake
that we're good quality.

00:33:45.523 --> 00:33:47.861
A lot of these attempts
to really polish up things

00:33:47.861 --> 00:33:49.319
are to fake that it's good quality,

00:33:49.319 --> 00:33:53.198
because to maybe the
buyer who's not the user,

00:33:53.198 --> 00:33:55.166
the buyer might superficially
look at something and say,

00:33:55.166 --> 00:33:57.152
"Oh, there's computer graphics,
that must be good quality,"

00:33:57.152 --> 00:33:59.150
but I think the big takeaway
from the Khan Academy

00:33:59.150 --> 00:34:00.517
if something is really going
to take on, it just has

00:34:00.517 --> 00:34:02.639
to purely cater to the user.

00:34:02.639 --> 00:34:07.653
Even if it is scrappy and not the most
professional thing, it'll still resonate.

00:34:07.653 --> 00:34:10.450
In terms of the process,
I'm now getting approached

00:34:10.450 --> 00:34:13.954
by a lot of - I want other
people other than myself to teach

00:34:13.954 --> 00:34:15.955
and I've been approached
by some medical schools

00:34:15.955 --> 00:34:19.818
and others, "We want to do
something like this in our program."

00:34:19.818 --> 00:34:24.151
I've sat through some of
those meetings and they go on.

00:34:24.151 --> 00:34:25.432
We have to talk to this department.

00:34:25.432 --> 00:34:29.537
So now my policy is when
anyone wants to say,

00:34:29.537 --> 00:34:31.568
"We think we have some
people who might be able

00:34:31.568 --> 00:34:33.736
"to make videos and we want to use them,"

00:34:33.736 --> 00:34:36.899
I say, "No preliminary meetings,
just come to my office,

00:34:36.899 --> 00:34:39.151
"I'll go take a walk, and make the videos.

00:34:39.151 --> 00:34:42.517
"I'll show you how to do it," and I
just want them to start making videos.

00:34:42.517 --> 00:34:43.847
They're like, "Wait, we haven't planned."

00:34:43.847 --> 00:34:45.901
I was like, "No, they teach these classes.

00:34:45.901 --> 00:34:47.852
"Just tell them to come
make a 10 minute video

00:34:47.852 --> 00:34:51.521
"and then we'll talk about
how we can improve them."

00:34:51.521 --> 00:34:53.358
It kind of scares these people,

00:34:53.358 --> 00:34:59.298
the fact that they might actually
produce something. (laughter)

00:34:59.298 --> 00:35:00.818
I think that's the take.

00:35:00.818 --> 00:35:03.870
Even in our organization, since
we're such a small organization,

00:35:03.870 --> 00:35:08.540
we're like six people, going
on eight or seven people now.

00:35:08.872 --> 00:35:12.806
We're very bandwidth constrained,
so we're starting to -

00:35:13.008 --> 00:35:14.423
I tell Shantanu, who's our
president, if me and him

00:35:14.423 --> 00:35:15.756
are in the same meeting at the same time,

00:35:15.756 --> 00:35:19.211
there's something wrong with our process.

00:35:19.211 --> 00:35:22.604
We force people to go on walks
for meetings, so it's a fixed -

00:35:22.604 --> 00:35:24.589
I don't want to -

00:35:24.589 --> 00:35:26.423
Jeff: By all means (crosstalk)

00:35:26.423 --> 00:35:28.008
Sal: Okay, yeah, we do that.

00:35:28.008 --> 00:35:30.894
A lot of the (crosstalk)

00:35:30.894 --> 00:35:32.340
It's funny, if it's an important meeting,

00:35:32.340 --> 00:35:34.007
I say I'm going to go
to El Camino and back.

00:35:34.007 --> 00:35:37.563
If it's a shady meeting I'm
going to the train stop and back.

00:35:37.563 --> 00:35:46.316
(crosstalk) (laughter)

00:35:46.316 --> 00:35:47.713
You kind of know where
you fit in the hierarchy

00:35:47.713 --> 00:35:50.483
(laughter) how long of a walk.

00:35:50.483 --> 00:35:52.651
The other thing is we actually
want to eat our own dog food,

00:35:52.651 --> 00:35:54.852
which is the reason why
we're able to scale,

00:35:54.852 --> 00:35:57.588
why such a small organization
is able to, on some level,

00:35:57.588 --> 00:36:00.391
educate two million kids and
maybe 200 million kids eventually,

00:36:00.391 --> 00:36:02.595
or whatever, is that we're
using these technologies.

00:36:02.595 --> 00:36:06.066
Even our board meetings,
right now our board meetings,

00:36:06.066 --> 00:36:07.454
we spend three hours
just giving an update.

00:36:07.454 --> 00:36:10.859
I'm like, "This is silly, I'm
just going to make YouTube videos,

00:36:10.859 --> 00:36:13.327
"explaining what we've
been up to the last week."

00:36:13.327 --> 00:36:14.998
I have the screen - Huh?

00:36:14.998 --> 00:36:17.363
(unintelligible) It's a
roadshow and our board can pause

00:36:17.363 --> 00:36:23.370
and repeat it and now
(laughter) we're thinking

00:36:23.370 --> 00:36:25.776
of making this a practice
across the organization,

00:36:25.776 --> 00:36:28.242
where we're going to
get everyone Camtasia,

00:36:28.242 --> 00:36:29.443
and everyone at the end of the week,

00:36:29.443 --> 00:36:31.578
instead of writing me an email, like,

00:36:31.578 --> 00:36:32.912
"Hey, this is what I've been up to."

00:36:32.912 --> 00:36:34.282
They'll have their computer right there,

00:36:34.282 --> 00:36:36.717
"This is what I'm working
on," and just archive it.

00:36:36.717 --> 00:36:40.255
That way when we go into meetings,
we're all on the same page,

00:36:40.255 --> 00:36:41.423
we know what everyone's been up to.

00:36:41.423 --> 00:36:42.755
If someone says something
that's unfamiliar,

00:36:42.755 --> 00:36:44.874
I don't have to pause the
meeting, I can go back

00:36:44.874 --> 00:36:48.229
and see what they're up to and
actually get a much better -

00:36:48.229 --> 00:36:50.264
Actually, I've told a
bunch of people this.

00:36:50.264 --> 00:36:52.501
I have a buddy who's
working at another startup

00:36:52.501 --> 00:36:54.503
and I told him this idea
and he bought into it

00:36:54.503 --> 00:36:58.820
and he told their CEO, because she
wanted him to write a white paper

00:36:58.820 --> 00:37:01.607
about what he's up to and he's like,

00:37:01.607 --> 00:37:03.206
"Well how about I do a screencast,

00:37:03.206 --> 00:37:04.945
"because now you can pause, repeat.

00:37:04.945 --> 00:37:07.816
"It'll be me explaining it as
a human being and I can show -"

00:37:07.816 --> 00:37:08.849
It was funny, they had a lot of,

00:37:08.849 --> 00:37:11.290
"No, that's silly, it
needs to be a white paper,"

00:37:11.290 --> 00:37:14.122
but no it doesn't, it
should really just be -

00:37:14.122 --> 00:37:16.691
It takes 10 minutes to
make a 10 minute video,

00:37:16.691 --> 00:37:18.791
especially if it's just
for internal consumption,

00:37:18.791 --> 00:37:23.195
as opposed to a day to write a white
paper that no one's going to read.

00:37:23.195 --> 00:37:25.313
Yeah, that's what we're up to.

00:37:25.313 --> 00:37:29.059
Jeff: I was just reminded of
effectiveness of the RSA animations,

00:37:29.059 --> 00:37:35.155
which is very similar, in terms
of mapping out and (crosstalk)

00:37:35.155 --> 00:37:37.608
You hear folks, a lot of people
in the audience today, I'm sure,

00:37:37.608 --> 00:37:39.012
they'll rave about them.

00:37:39.012 --> 00:37:44.539
They'll say, "Have you seen this
on motivation?" (unintelligible)

00:37:44.539 --> 00:37:47.403
Audience Member: Hey Sal,
thanks for being here.

00:37:47.403 --> 00:37:49.834
A few weeks ago, we watched
Waiting for Superman

00:37:49.834 --> 00:37:53.330
here at LinkedIn and it
was incredibly moving.

00:37:53.330 --> 00:37:54.511
Sal: Depressing. (laughs)

00:37:54.511 --> 00:37:57.694
Audience Member: Yeah, very depressing.

00:37:57.694 --> 00:37:59.248
I learned about the Khan Academy

00:37:59.248 --> 00:38:02.249
after watching that
movie here at LinkedIn.

00:38:02.249 --> 00:38:05.701
After spending time on your
site, it was pretty obvious to me

00:38:05.701 --> 00:38:09.284
that what you have developed
can be the super hero solution

00:38:09.284 --> 00:38:11.925
for schools that don't have resources,

00:38:11.925 --> 00:38:14.897
for kids that don't have
resources, to help them learn.

00:38:14.897 --> 00:38:18.433
I'm just wondering if part
of the Khan Academy's charter

00:38:18.433 --> 00:38:21.768
is to get those kinds of
resources into the hands of kids

00:38:21.768 --> 00:38:23.670
where they don't have computers at home

00:38:23.670 --> 00:38:26.174
or the school systems
don't have computers.

00:38:26.174 --> 00:38:27.452
Is that part of the conversation?

00:38:27.452 --> 00:38:30.116
Sal: Yeah, absolutely.

00:38:30.116 --> 00:38:31.124
There's a couple of things here.

00:38:31.124 --> 00:38:32.533
One of the things, this is something

00:38:32.533 --> 00:38:34.566
that we're very protective
of as an organization,

00:38:34.566 --> 00:38:36.485
is the reason why I think we're resonating

00:38:36.485 --> 00:38:38.535
where a lot of other attempts,
governmental attempts,

00:38:38.535 --> 00:38:40.618
NGO attempts, for profit
attempts have all failed,

00:38:40.618 --> 00:38:44.092
is that everyone else is
trying to reform the beast.

00:38:44.092 --> 00:38:45.860
They're trying to go in
there and chisel at it

00:38:45.860 --> 00:38:49.329
and lobby this or that and all the rest.

00:38:49.329 --> 00:38:52.285
The reason why I think we've
worked is we've ignored the beast.

00:38:52.285 --> 00:38:55.836
We've just done our own thing
and go straight to the student.

00:38:55.836 --> 00:38:57.202
At the same time, this Los Altos thing,

00:38:57.202 --> 00:38:59.285
which kind of fell in
our lap, proves that no,

00:38:59.285 --> 00:39:01.308
this can help the beast.

00:39:01.308 --> 00:39:07.382
I shouldn't call it the
beast anymore. (laughter)

00:39:07.382 --> 00:39:12.552
What we're doing is, and this
wasn't our plan even a month ago,

00:39:12.552 --> 00:39:14.435
but especially the TED talk
took this to the next level,

00:39:14.435 --> 00:39:16.833
we are building a rollout SWAT team,

00:39:16.833 --> 00:39:18.851
and what we're going to do
over the next six months -

00:39:18.851 --> 00:39:20.193
The other thing we want to be careful of

00:39:20.193 --> 00:39:22.305
is not rolling out too fast and ruining.

00:39:22.305 --> 00:39:23.805
We're the Trader Joe's model.

00:39:23.805 --> 00:39:25.688
We want a community to really
want us and we're like,

00:39:25.688 --> 00:39:28.895
"Okay, you've got to
give us the right space,"

00:39:30.139 --> 00:39:34.094
We want the SWAT team over
the next 6 to 18 months,

00:39:34.094 --> 00:39:37.072
we're reached out now by about
10 school districts a day

00:39:37.072 --> 00:39:39.008
who want to do this and so we want to pick

00:39:39.008 --> 00:39:43.852
the 10 or 15 that are the
most likely to be a success.

00:39:43.852 --> 00:39:47.356
Hopefully they won't mainly be affluent
school districts like Los Altos.

00:39:47.356 --> 00:39:49.884
We're looking for underserved communities,

00:39:49.884 --> 00:39:51.565
some charter schools,
some independent schools,

00:39:51.565 --> 00:39:53.763
some regular middle class private
schools, all of the above.

00:39:53.763 --> 00:39:58.031
Some fancy private schools, and
we're actually going district wide

00:39:58.031 --> 00:40:00.050
in fourth, fifth, and sixth
grade in Los Altos, as well.

00:40:00.050 --> 00:40:02.740
So if you have a fourth or fifth
or sixth grader in Los Altos,

00:40:02.740 --> 00:40:08.428
you'll start hearing me in your
house whether you like it or not.

00:40:09.186 --> 00:40:10.510
We want to do that and once we have that

00:40:10.510 --> 00:40:12.926
and we learn more, we can productize it.

00:40:12.926 --> 00:40:16.166
Then, we're going to explore how
it can become a more massive role.

00:40:16.166 --> 00:40:18.831
The narrative throughout
this is we're also going

00:40:18.831 --> 00:40:20.485
to make it more and more self-service.

00:40:20.485 --> 00:40:22.122
Like the first question you had asked,

00:40:22.122 --> 00:40:25.581
it can be used in any
school district tomorrow.

00:40:25.581 --> 00:40:27.829
To some degree, that's
another volunteer opportunity.

00:40:27.829 --> 00:40:30.079
If your school district isn't
doing it and you think they should,

00:40:30.079 --> 00:40:32.662
you guys can become
the ambassadors for it.

00:40:32.662 --> 00:40:34.248
You guys all have the same -

00:40:34.248 --> 00:40:36.079
If you guys go to our website,
it'll be pretty obvious

00:40:36.079 --> 00:40:38.137
how you could implement
this in a classroom.

00:40:38.137 --> 00:40:40.412
You could be that person that
goes to the school district

00:40:40.412 --> 00:40:43.209
and say, "Look, we can do this."

00:40:43.209 --> 00:40:45.414
The Los Altos people are awesome
about other people coming in

00:40:45.414 --> 00:40:47.945
and observing the classrooms.

00:40:47.945 --> 00:40:51.005
If it's local, you say,
"Hey, why don't we go meet

00:40:51.005 --> 00:40:53.280
"with those Los Altos people,
observe their classroom,

00:40:53.280 --> 00:40:54.332
"and then we'll implement it here,"

00:40:54.332 --> 00:40:55.434
and you guys can shepherd it,

00:40:55.434 --> 00:40:58.365
make sure their firewall is set
up, whatever, so it happens.

00:40:58.365 --> 00:41:00.865
I think that, by itself,
could be a pretty, actually,

00:41:00.865 --> 00:41:04.365
that might be the most
powerful way to volunteer.

00:41:04.365 --> 00:41:06.200
Jeff: Sal, how do teachers respond to it?

00:41:06.200 --> 00:41:08.365
Do they feel like it's an incredible tool

00:41:08.365 --> 00:41:12.150
that helps take their
classrooms to the next level?

00:41:12.150 --> 00:41:13.652
At times, do they feel threatened by it?

00:41:13.652 --> 00:41:15.088
What kind of response do you get?

00:41:15.088 --> 00:41:17.365
Sal: We get a positive selection bias.

00:41:17.365 --> 00:41:19.057
The ones that reach out to us are the ones

00:41:19.057 --> 00:41:20.726
that are probably using us on some level

00:41:20.726 --> 00:41:22.865
and those teachers are
excited, more excited

00:41:22.865 --> 00:41:25.207
than I even thought, originally.

00:41:25.718 --> 00:41:28.769
I think the really skilled
teachers, the reason

00:41:28.769 --> 00:41:30.066
why they went into teaching is they wanted

00:41:30.066 --> 00:41:35.233
to form bonds with students, they
wanted to be creative themselves

00:41:35.233 --> 00:41:38.927
and test the children's creativity,
but when they go into a classroom,

00:41:38.927 --> 00:41:41.131
there's 30 kids, all different
levels, they have to do

00:41:41.131 --> 00:41:43.397
all of this classroom
management, "Be quiet,"

00:41:43.397 --> 00:41:46.317
and actually, that's almost more of the -

00:41:46.317 --> 00:41:49.105
If I had to become a teacher
tomorrow in a real classroom,

00:41:49.105 --> 00:41:50.650
that's the stuff I would have to learn.

00:41:50.650 --> 00:41:52.651
I actually did volunteer once in college

00:41:52.651 --> 00:41:54.877
and literally within ten
minutes, all of the kids

00:41:54.877 --> 00:41:58.114
were standing on top of the table
and I had no idea what I did wrong.

00:41:58.114 --> 00:42:00.047
It was like this ...

00:42:00.047 --> 00:42:02.066
The teachers want to be
this liberated person

00:42:02.066 --> 00:42:06.085
who can form bonds, who can
dig in, who have the data,

00:42:06.085 --> 00:42:08.223
so the teachers who've
seen that, they love it.

00:42:08.223 --> 00:42:09.492
These Los Altos teachers love it.

00:42:09.492 --> 00:42:11.962
I spoke to all of the Los Altos
elementary school teachers

00:42:11.962 --> 00:42:14.336
and they're pretty much,
as far as I can tell,

00:42:14.336 --> 00:42:16.033
it seems like they're on board.

00:42:16.033 --> 00:42:20.971
I think the resistance comes from people

00:42:20.971 --> 00:42:22.919
who aren't familiar with
what we're trying to do

00:42:22.919 --> 00:42:26.745
and they just see the headline,
they just get a glimpse

00:42:26.745 --> 00:42:29.379
of kind of what it's
about, so unfortunately

00:42:29.379 --> 00:42:34.251
there have been headlines like,

00:42:34.251 --> 00:42:36.722
"Is This the Solution to
Our Education Problem?"

00:42:36.722 --> 00:42:41.192
We think it is on some level, but
people have a knee jerk reaction

00:42:41.192 --> 00:42:43.494
to this kind of panacea type thing.

00:42:43.494 --> 00:42:46.419
They're like, "Oh no, this
isn't it and this is going to be

00:42:46.419 --> 00:42:47.922
"just drill and kill learning."

00:42:47.922 --> 00:42:49.399
They'll say all of that type of thing.

00:42:49.399 --> 00:42:51.636
There's obviously a lot of people on -

00:42:51.636 --> 00:42:54.420
We try to stay out of political
debates, but there's a lot of people

00:42:54.420 --> 00:42:57.558
who view Khan Academy
as an empowering tool

00:42:57.558 --> 00:43:04.903
against things like teachers'
unions or against things like -

00:43:06.283 --> 00:43:09.307
When someone in a teachers'
union sees someone else say,

00:43:09.307 --> 00:43:12.740
"Oh, now that Khan Academy's here,
this is going to get you guys,"

00:43:12.740 --> 00:43:15.581
they immediately react against it.

00:43:16.516 --> 00:43:19.234
We try not to enter those
debates, but what I will say is

00:43:19.234 --> 00:43:21.233
no, we're empowering the teachers.

00:43:21.233 --> 00:43:22.901
It's going to free up their time.

00:43:22.901 --> 00:43:25.817
Right now, this is why teachers
are, I think, so frustrated

00:43:25.817 --> 00:43:27.649
is every time there's a
new study that comes out

00:43:27.649 --> 00:43:29.805
that shows that schools are falling behind

00:43:29.805 --> 00:43:32.650
and we're falling behind Senegal
or whatever, some other country,

00:43:32.650 --> 00:43:37.539
the reaction of policymakers
is we have to micromanage more.

00:43:37.539 --> 00:43:40.651
The belief is that the micromanagement
is all around the focus

00:43:40.651 --> 00:43:43.444
of de-risking the worst teachers,

00:43:43.444 --> 00:43:46.682
de-risking the worst
students, on some level.

00:43:46.682 --> 00:43:50.971
What it does is it completely
straps everyone else.

00:43:50.971 --> 00:43:53.693
What we're doing now is
we're liberating everyone.

00:43:53.693 --> 00:43:55.621
You can cater to everyone
and to some degree,

00:43:55.621 --> 00:43:58.400
you are de-risking the
teacher who might not have,

00:43:58.400 --> 00:43:59.652
and I'm not saying this is most teachers,

00:43:59.652 --> 00:44:01.362
but in any industry there is a bell curve

00:44:01.362 --> 00:44:04.471
and there is the bottom 5%
of teachers and 5% of kids

00:44:04.471 --> 00:44:06.247
are in front of the bottom 5% of teachers

00:44:06.247 --> 00:44:09.499
and you can de-risk them because
now they have an alternative

00:44:09.499 --> 00:44:13.880
and now the top 95%, or the top
50%, or the top 5% of teachers

00:44:13.880 --> 00:44:17.050
are liberated to fully express
their abilities, their creativity.

00:44:17.050 --> 00:44:20.750
They could think of stuff like my
trading game or even better stuff.

00:44:21.416 --> 00:44:23.898
I would say on the whole, the ones
that have watched the TED talks,

00:44:23.898 --> 00:44:27.235
the ones that have understood what
we're trying to do are pretty excited.

00:44:27.235 --> 00:44:30.004
The one other dimension
is, and this is happening

00:44:30.004 --> 00:44:33.364
in Los Altos classroom,
there's fifth graders doing

00:44:33.364 --> 00:44:36.220
the chain rule in a Los Altos classroom.

00:44:36.220 --> 00:44:38.449
As a teacher, that can
be a little daunting.

00:44:38.449 --> 00:44:39.865
You're a fifth grade
teacher, you signed up

00:44:39.865 --> 00:44:41.781
to be a fifth grade
teacher, and there's a kid

00:44:41.781 --> 00:44:44.780
doing calculus in the room.

00:44:44.780 --> 00:44:47.032
What we saw from the one
teacher when we observed it,

00:44:47.032 --> 00:44:50.004
she literally, and he was
marked by the dashboard as red,

00:44:50.004 --> 00:44:51.501
he wasn't understanding the chain rule,

00:44:51.501 --> 00:44:55.241
so she's like, "I'd better intervene,"
but what was really powerful

00:44:55.241 --> 00:44:59.781
was that she went and
she said, "You know what?

00:44:59.781 --> 00:45:03.282
"I haven't seen this since college
and I forgot how to do this

00:45:03.282 --> 00:45:04.515
"or what this was all about.

00:45:04.515 --> 00:45:06.531
"Why don't we learn it together?"

00:45:06.531 --> 00:45:08.656
I was there observe -

00:45:08.656 --> 00:45:10.991
It immediately clicked with the kid.

00:45:10.991 --> 00:45:13.394
It almost felt like he respected
the teacher ten times more

00:45:13.394 --> 00:45:16.189
because she was willing
to let down her guard

00:45:16.189 --> 00:45:21.418
as the source of all correct
answers in the world.

00:45:22.402 --> 00:45:24.588
A teacher has to feel comfortable.

00:45:24.588 --> 00:45:27.694
Actually, on the same
line, there was a reporter

00:45:27.694 --> 00:45:30.103
who was doing a story on one
of the fifth grade classrooms

00:45:30.103 --> 00:45:32.807
and there was one girl in there
who was doing trigonometry

00:45:32.807 --> 00:45:34.498
and the reporter sits
down next to her and says,

00:45:34.498 --> 00:45:36.890
"Do you think this is fifth grade math?"

00:45:36.890 --> 00:45:44.274
and the girl goes, "No, I think
it's sixth grade." (laughter)

00:45:44.274 --> 00:45:45.890
Jeff: Go ahead.

00:45:45.890 --> 00:45:48.879
Ron: Thank you for being here.

00:45:48.879 --> 00:45:51.917
I watched your TED talk twice.

00:45:51.917 --> 00:45:55.224
Once I discovered it on
LinkedIn today, by the way,

00:45:55.224 --> 00:45:59.025
and it was like 11 PM,
something like that.

00:45:59.025 --> 00:46:01.991
I watched it, I was completely blown away,

00:46:01.991 --> 00:46:04.496
I called my wife, "I need
to show you something,"

00:46:04.496 --> 00:46:07.199
so we watched it together the second time.

00:46:07.199 --> 00:46:13.269
It made me deeply depressed (laughter)

00:46:13.269 --> 00:46:24.048
and I love your system (crosstalk)

00:46:24.048 --> 00:46:29.554
The problem here is that you
have two aspects in this system.

00:46:29.554 --> 00:46:32.353
One is you learn at your pace.

00:46:32.353 --> 00:46:35.019
The second one, you
exercise collaboratively,

00:46:35.019 --> 00:46:38.398
in the room with other kids.

00:46:38.398 --> 00:46:41.853
It needs to be implemented in
the school system in some way.

00:46:41.853 --> 00:46:45.570
You can't do that without
implementing in the school system.

00:46:45.570 --> 00:46:48.138
School systems are slow.

00:46:48.138 --> 00:46:50.436
My kid is four and a half years old.

00:46:50.436 --> 00:46:55.676
I want her to do that in two years.

00:46:56.046 --> 00:46:59.313
I don't live in Los Altos. (laughter)

00:46:59.313 --> 00:47:01.717
Sal: Neither do I.

00:47:01.717 --> 00:47:03.485
I have another interesting
story to tell you.

00:47:03.485 --> 00:47:07.220
I don't live in Los Altos, either, but
I'll say I have another interesting -

00:47:07.220 --> 00:47:10.592
Ron: Actually, I was growing
up in the third world

00:47:10.592 --> 00:47:12.758
and I made it here to the Silicon Valley,

00:47:12.758 --> 00:47:16.300
which I think is quite
an achievement for myself

00:47:16.300 --> 00:47:19.501
and now I feel as if I'm
back to the third world,

00:47:19.501 --> 00:47:23.345
because my kid will not be that genius.

00:47:23.345 --> 00:47:28.744
It will create a few million genius
kids and a couple of billions

00:47:28.744 --> 00:47:32.258
who are as dumb as they
are right now. (laughing)

00:47:32.258 --> 00:47:37.753
Sorry. (crosstalk)

