00:54:36.745 --> 00:54:38.448
I know your focus is primary education,

00:54:38.448 --> 00:54:42.584
but I wanted to ask you a little bit
about our university system here.

00:54:42.584 --> 00:54:46.204
There's been a lot of talk recently
about a bubble in higher education.

00:54:46.204 --> 00:54:47.653
Sal: Yeah, Peter Thiel.

00:54:47.653 --> 00:54:49.204
Audience Member: Exactly.

00:54:49.204 --> 00:54:51.036
College costs are ballooning.

00:54:51.036 --> 00:54:57.121
As a society, we're placing more
and more emphasis on credentials.

00:54:57.121 --> 00:54:58.597
Ivy league is the big thing.

00:54:58.597 --> 00:55:01.704
Everybody wants their kids
to go to the ivy league.

00:55:01.704 --> 00:55:04.124
Do you have any thoughts about
reforming that kind of system?

00:55:04.124 --> 00:55:05.738
Well, not reform, because I know -

00:55:05.738 --> 00:55:06.623
Sal: Reinventing.

00:55:06.623 --> 00:55:10.204
Audience Member: Reinventing
that system specifically

00:55:10.204 --> 00:55:14.139
and maybe if there's
anything we need to change

00:55:14.139 --> 00:55:17.617
our way of thinking, as a culture,
so that we can get back on track.

00:55:17.617 --> 00:55:22.014
Sal: Yeah, to give you all
background, Peter Thiel,

00:55:22.014 --> 00:55:24.249
one of the founders of PayPal,
he runs Clarion Capital,

00:55:24.249 --> 00:55:26.251
another hedge fund guy.

00:55:26.251 --> 00:55:30.088
He's been pretty vocal about
this bubble in higher education.

00:55:30.088 --> 00:55:32.026
He's been good at spotting
the previous bubbles.

00:55:32.026 --> 00:55:34.141
The housing bubble, the tech
bubble, and all of that.

00:55:34.141 --> 00:55:37.807
It's a bubble because
people are willing to pay

00:55:37.807 --> 00:55:39.599
ridiculous amounts of money in perception

00:55:39.599 --> 00:55:42.307
that it's a good investment
when it really isn't,

00:55:42.307 --> 00:55:44.307
which is what a bubble is.

00:55:44.307 --> 00:55:45.440
That's true with the housing bubble,

00:55:45.440 --> 00:55:48.253
that's true of the tech bubble.

00:55:49.390 --> 00:55:52.413
Beyond just talking about it,
his attempt at disrupting it,

00:55:52.413 --> 00:55:54.624
which I think is in the right direction,

00:55:54.624 --> 00:55:58.527
but I don't think it goes quite
enough, is he started this program,

00:55:58.527 --> 00:56:01.126
where he's targeting the same
kids who would otherwise go

00:56:01.126 --> 00:56:03.509
to Stanford or MIT or
Harvard or wherever and say,

00:56:03.509 --> 00:56:05.720
"Look, I'll pay you 100 grand
if you drop out of school

00:56:05.720 --> 00:56:07.965
"and come start a business."

00:56:09.059 --> 00:56:13.024
He's trying to make it so
there's something very desirable,

00:56:13.024 --> 00:56:18.425
like very prestigious to have, and
probably will help your career,

00:56:18.425 --> 00:56:21.298
that doesn't cost money, that you
would give up that other thing,

00:56:21.298 --> 00:56:22.425
you would give up the college degree

00:56:22.425 --> 00:56:24.091
and this might become more desirable.

00:56:24.091 --> 00:56:28.944
I think what would really work,
to take his thing to the -

00:56:28.944 --> 00:56:33.016
I've thrown it out as a crazy
idea three or four weeks ago

00:56:33.016 --> 00:56:34.350
and now it's getting a little less crazy

00:56:34.350 --> 00:56:38.753
is I think it would be
awesome to start a university,

00:56:38.753 --> 00:56:42.998
for lack of a better
word, in Mountain View.

00:56:44.661 --> 00:56:46.574
This first university, I don't
want to make it sound elitist,

00:56:46.574 --> 00:56:48.698
but it would focus on the
best and the brightest.

00:56:48.698 --> 00:56:50.531
It would focus on the same
kids that are applying

00:56:50.531 --> 00:56:52.679
to Stanford and MIT and Harvard
and all of this right now.

00:56:52.679 --> 00:56:54.363
I'll take a tangent on why I say that,

00:56:54.363 --> 00:56:57.502
because I think that's the
only way you can disrupt.

00:56:58.086 --> 00:57:01.097
The goal here, instead of these
students paying $50,000 a year

00:57:01.097 --> 00:57:03.262
and going into debt, they would be paid.

00:57:03.262 --> 00:57:05.976
The reason why I say that is if
you can make the best education

00:57:05.976 --> 00:57:09.847
have negative tuition, then
it's a geeky calculus analogy,

00:57:09.847 --> 00:57:13.679
by the squeeze theorem,
literally, how can anyone else

00:57:13.679 --> 00:57:18.929
justify charging anything, if the
best education is negative tuition?

00:57:18.929 --> 00:57:22.728
You get people to come
in and their curriculum

00:57:22.728 --> 00:57:27.012
is literally six months at
LinkedIn, six months at Google.

00:57:27.012 --> 00:57:30.015
They work in software engineering,
they work in product management,

00:57:30.015 --> 00:57:34.238
they work in marketing, they work
in PR, they work in accounting.

00:57:34.238 --> 00:57:37.083
Six months at Apple, six
months working for a VC firm,

00:57:37.083 --> 00:57:42.813
six months developing iPad apps,
or whatever and they are paid.

00:57:42.813 --> 00:57:45.885
Some of the money goes to the
students, maybe 30 grand a year

00:57:45.885 --> 00:57:47.385
and some of it goes to the university

00:57:47.385 --> 00:57:49.554
to set up the environment
that you should have.

00:57:49.554 --> 00:57:51.417
It's not this purely commercial thing.

00:57:51.417 --> 00:57:53.667
You have all of the things that
we all liked about college.

00:57:53.667 --> 00:57:57.528
You have a campus, you have
pretty trees to read books under,

00:57:57.528 --> 00:58:03.249
(laughter) you have venues to meet
your future husband or wife. (laughter)

00:58:03.249 --> 00:58:10.182
And you have a scaffold
of truly academic material

00:58:10.182 --> 00:58:13.001
that you can do at your own pace,
something like the Khan Academy.

00:58:13.001 --> 00:58:14.644
The faculty and you have seminars.

00:58:14.644 --> 00:58:16.167
"Hey, I'm working on
a project at LinkedIn,

00:58:16.167 --> 00:58:18.333
"but you know what, this is going
to require some signal processing.

00:58:18.333 --> 00:58:19.773
"I don't know signal processing."

00:58:19.773 --> 00:58:23.334
I go back to the campus, there
are either other students there,

00:58:23.334 --> 00:58:25.833
there's Khan Academy
resources, or there are mentors

00:58:25.833 --> 00:58:28.961
in the valley who are willing to
work with me on signal processing.

00:58:28.961 --> 00:58:30.917
Then, I learn it.

00:58:30.917 --> 00:58:32.418
You go through this, so
what's going to happen

00:58:32.418 --> 00:58:35.135
is these students are going to
end up finishing not with debt.

00:58:35.135 --> 00:58:36.417
They're going to have money saved,

00:58:36.417 --> 00:58:37.901
they're going to be way more desirable

00:58:37.901 --> 00:58:40.304
by this whole slew of companies,

00:58:40.304 --> 00:58:42.334
and they have the downside protection,

00:58:42.334 --> 00:58:44.307
because they still had a little
bit of an academic scaffold.

00:58:44.307 --> 00:58:46.644
They'll do well on the MCAT,
the GRE, if they decide

00:58:46.644 --> 00:58:51.001
they want to become a doctor or
a lawyer, they can still do that.

00:58:51.001 --> 00:58:57.720
I think if you do that, it'll be pretty
hard for Stanford to justify charging ...

00:58:57.720 --> 00:58:59.417
The other thing is, you could
go right out of the gate,

00:58:59.417 --> 00:59:01.059
because if you get the employers involved,

