00:59:39.345 --> 00:59:41.851
I know some people had
good results going there.

00:59:41.851 --> 00:59:43.049
I don't know if you've looked at that.

00:59:43.049 --> 00:59:44.728
Sal: I think the problem there, and
actually, I know Olin pretty well.

00:59:44.728 --> 00:59:49.095
My adviser at MIT actually ended
up becoming a professor at Olin.

00:59:49.590 --> 00:59:52.213
I think the problem is ...

00:59:52.213 --> 00:59:54.379
The reason why people are
paying $200,000 right now

00:59:54.379 --> 00:59:59.816
is to have a signal to send to
the job market that I kick butt.

00:59:59.816 --> 01:00:01.921
Even though Olin, I haven't gone to Olin,

01:00:01.921 --> 01:00:04.381
but I can imagine it's
probably a very good education,

01:00:04.381 --> 01:00:06.297
that's not why people
are spending $200,000.

01:00:06.297 --> 01:00:10.976
They want that signal, I went
to MIT, I went to Cal Tech.

01:00:10.976 --> 01:00:12.215
It's the brand.

01:00:12.215 --> 01:00:14.947
Olin has a problem of that
and it also has the problem

01:00:14.947 --> 01:00:17.082
with the connections,
I don't know if Google,

01:00:17.082 --> 01:00:19.133
maybe Google does, but I
don't know if Goldman Sachs

01:00:19.133 --> 01:00:21.383
recruits at Olin, though
maybe they should,

01:00:21.383 --> 01:00:25.321
because they don't know what Olin is.

01:00:26.132 --> 01:00:28.626
I think the key thing would have
to have some type of partnership

01:00:28.626 --> 01:00:30.692
with very marquee recruits.

01:00:30.692 --> 01:00:34.378
If you get an ecosystem
of ten of the top tier,

01:00:34.378 --> 01:00:36.503
the companies everyone wants to work for,

01:00:36.503 --> 01:00:38.567
the other companies, the
next tier of companies

01:00:38.567 --> 01:00:41.294
are going to say, "Wait, if
Google or LinkedIn's getting

01:00:41.294 --> 01:00:44.462
"all of its talent there, we
better get our talent there, too.

01:00:44.462 --> 01:00:47.209
"We don't want to look like
we're getting the scraps."

01:00:47.209 --> 01:00:51.127
I think it's very important to
build the whole ecosystem there.

01:00:51.127 --> 01:00:52.294
Actually, the big difference would be

01:00:52.294 --> 01:00:56.251
that the projects would be
stuff that actually matters.

01:00:56.251 --> 01:00:59.823
In the past, if I would have
recommended this 50 years ago,

01:00:59.823 --> 01:01:01.257
people would have said, "Oh my God,

01:01:01.257 --> 01:01:03.292
"but you're making people
do vocational things.

01:01:03.292 --> 01:01:06.128
"That's horrible, it's
commercial," but the reality is

01:01:06.128 --> 01:01:07.628
the stuff that's going
on at LinkedIn right now,

01:01:07.628 --> 01:01:09.628
the analytics, the software
engineering, the marketing,

01:01:09.628 --> 01:01:12.795
the stuff that's going on at
Google, it's more intellectual

01:01:12.795 --> 01:01:15.106
than the software engineering
projects that we worked on

01:01:15.106 --> 01:01:16.294
when we were undergrads.

01:01:16.294 --> 01:01:18.515
It's more intellectual
than almost anything,

01:01:18.515 --> 01:01:24.126
the made up projects that a
university gives you right now.

01:01:24.126 --> 01:01:25.301
I think if you build the whole eco -

01:01:25.301 --> 01:01:27.418
I think Silicon Valley is
the perfect place to do it.

01:01:27.418 --> 01:01:28.960
The one thing that I've
discovered through Khan Academy

01:01:28.960 --> 01:01:32.735
is there's a lot of people who
made it, who are super smart,

01:01:32.735 --> 01:01:36.494
who are orbiting the valley just
looking for someone to mentor,

01:01:36.494 --> 01:01:39.164
looking to disrupt things a little bit.

01:01:39.164 --> 01:01:41.329
You can imagine, instead
of this school showing off

01:01:41.329 --> 01:01:43.712
about how many Nobel Laureates
they have on their faculty,

01:01:43.712 --> 01:01:50.004
they say, "No, we have the CEOs
of this company and this company.

01:01:51.209 --> 01:01:53.144
"These entrepreneurs and these people

01:01:53.144 --> 01:01:55.633
"who've done amazing things in
the world, this is our faculty.

01:01:55.633 --> 01:01:58.704
"These are the people you have
access to as your mentors."

01:01:58.704 --> 01:01:59.918
I think you do something like that,

01:01:59.918 --> 01:02:02.454
I think it would be pretty
hard to compete with.

01:02:02.454 --> 01:02:03.590
Audience Member: Thanks so much.

01:02:03.590 --> 01:02:04.487
Sal: Yeah, sure.

01:02:04.487 --> 01:02:06.369
Jeff: Okay, these are going to
be the last three questions.

01:02:06.369 --> 01:02:08.286
Sal's already stayed a little bit extra,

01:02:08.286 --> 01:02:10.229
but there have been some great questions.

01:02:10.229 --> 01:02:11.954
Audience Member: Yeah, thank
you very much for coming.

01:02:11.954 --> 01:02:15.200
I have a question going back to scale.

01:02:15.200 --> 01:02:18.454
Ron has given us a two year
deadline to grow very quickly.

01:02:18.454 --> 01:02:20.706
Sal: (laughing) Where
do you live, by the way?

01:02:20.706 --> 01:02:21.956
Ron: Palo Alto.

01:02:21.956 --> 01:02:28.289
Sal: Oh, yeah (laughter) a
very underserved community.

01:02:28.289 --> 01:02:33.781
Yeah, I think we might be
able to meet your goal.

01:02:35.041 --> 01:02:37.785
Audience Member: My
question is have you thought

01:02:37.785 --> 01:02:40.481
about making the Khan Academy
lectures more searchable,

01:02:40.481 --> 01:02:42.596
basically being able to
reach them more easily

01:02:42.596 --> 01:02:44.981
from other sites or
partnering with other sites

01:02:44.981 --> 01:02:47.398
or even your students themselves?

01:02:47.398 --> 01:02:50.699
Have you had any experiences
with them really growing

01:02:50.699 --> 01:02:53.565
your user base because they've shared

01:02:53.565 --> 01:02:55.379
their experience with someone else?

01:02:55.379 --> 01:02:57.850
Do you think that that's a
viable way to grow more quickly

01:02:57.850 --> 01:03:01.065
than actually getting an
entire educational institution

01:03:01.065 --> 01:03:03.898
to come on board and buy into this?

01:03:03.898 --> 01:03:06.647
Sal: Oh yeah, just to be clear,

01:03:06.647 --> 01:03:08.233
this is something we tell
our team the whole time.

01:03:08.233 --> 01:03:11.620
This roll out into
schools fell into our lap

01:03:11.620 --> 01:03:12.920
and we're like, "This is an opportunity

01:03:12.920 --> 01:03:15.066
and there's no obvious
resistance, so let's do it,"

01:03:15.066 --> 01:03:16.897
but our number one goal is actually that.

01:03:16.897 --> 01:03:20.149
It's actually the organic, word of
mouth, kids telling kids about it,

01:03:20.149 --> 01:03:24.622
teachers direct a student, a one
off kid or parent trying to learn,

01:03:24.622 --> 01:03:27.065
even homeschoolers, that still is.

01:03:27.065 --> 01:03:29.672
We want Khan Academy to,
if you have nothing else,

01:03:29.672 --> 01:03:33.006
you're still able to get an education.

01:03:33.006 --> 01:03:35.209
To ask the questions
about the searchability,

01:03:35.209 --> 01:03:38.147
that's something we're working on.

01:03:39.835 --> 01:03:42.097
2,200 videos, it's this
huge curation problem.

01:03:42.097 --> 01:03:45.754
We're figuring out ways
to categorize it better,

01:03:45.754 --> 01:03:47.422
ways to make it more searchable.

01:03:47.422 --> 01:03:50.058
We're getting transcripts on them
so they can be text searchable.

01:03:50.058 --> 01:03:52.089
The Google people have told
us that that's actually,

01:03:52.089 --> 01:03:54.159
it's unfortunate that
if you do a text search

01:03:54.159 --> 01:03:55.775
for alegbra right now, Khan Academy videos

01:03:55.775 --> 01:03:58.359
they don't even come up on the first page.

01:03:58.359 --> 01:04:00.275
All sorts of random stuff
because there's no text

01:04:00.275 --> 01:04:02.469
that says "parabola" and
all of this type of stuff.

01:04:02.469 --> 01:04:04.803
We're going to work on that so it becomes

01:04:04.803 --> 01:04:08.507
a lot more meaningfully searchable.

01:04:08.507 --> 01:04:10.417
Audience Member: Thanks.

01:04:10.743 --> 01:04:11.584
Audience Member: In terms of making

01:04:11.584 --> 01:04:15.646
the Academy's content more
palatable to the beast,

01:04:15.646 --> 01:04:17.988
is there any academic research going on,

01:04:17.988 --> 01:04:20.151
in terms of the efficacy of the program?

01:04:20.151 --> 01:04:25.622
Sal: Yeah, we're eager to do
more hardcore, rigorous studies.

01:04:25.622 --> 01:04:29.591
Even in Los Altos, I've
been broadly impressed

01:04:29.591 --> 01:04:32.331
with the whole Los Altos school system,

01:04:32.331 --> 01:04:34.871
from the teachers, the parents, all
the way up to the superintendent.

01:04:34.871 --> 01:04:37.502
They're not people who
get enamored with an idea

01:04:37.502 --> 01:04:40.362
and say, "Let's just go district
wide with it for the hell of it."

01:04:43.911 --> 01:04:46.753
The two seventh grade classes
who have been using it,

01:04:46.753 --> 01:04:49.863
they call it algebra readiness classes.

01:04:49.863 --> 01:04:51.532
These classes are actually,
I guess you'd call them,

01:04:51.532 --> 01:04:56.635
they're the students
not in the medium track.

01:04:56.635 --> 01:04:59.615
These students they did a before and after

01:04:59.615 --> 01:05:01.927
and these kids went from ...

01:05:01.927 --> 01:05:03.696
I forgot the exact numbers,
but it was on the order,

01:05:03.696 --> 01:05:06.334
I'm not exaggerating, like 20% proficiency

01:05:06.334 --> 01:05:11.036
of algebra and pre-algebra concepts
to, I think, it's like 80% on average.

01:05:11.036 --> 01:05:13.383
It's a dramatic change.

01:05:13.383 --> 01:05:14.740
They actually never had
these classes before,

01:05:14.740 --> 01:05:16.876
so they don't know what
happened in previous years,

01:05:16.876 --> 01:05:18.912
but that was pretty powerful for them.

01:05:18.912 --> 01:05:20.412
Audience Member: Even
instead of doing both fifth

01:05:20.412 --> 01:05:23.240
and both seventh grade
class, if you were to do

01:05:23.240 --> 01:05:26.074
one fifth, sixth, and seventh
grade class and not the other

01:05:26.074 --> 01:05:27.079
and do cohort -

01:05:27.079 --> 01:05:28.441
Sal: Exactly, the fifth
grade we're doing that.

01:05:28.441 --> 01:05:32.423
They had a fifth grade assessment
that they do every year.

01:05:34.569 --> 01:05:36.872
The results came out and
our fifth grade classes,

01:05:36.872 --> 01:05:38.455
despite the fact that we weren't -

01:05:38.455 --> 01:05:40.039
I was stressed about it,
because the other classes

01:05:40.039 --> 01:05:41.788
were literally teaching to the test.

01:05:41.788 --> 01:05:43.455
In our classes, they were
doing this crazy stuff

01:05:43.455 --> 01:05:45.291
that had nothing to do with the exam.

01:05:45.291 --> 01:05:49.239
Ours did at least or better than those.

01:05:50.015 --> 01:05:52.553
The good thing is we're
definitely not damaging anything,

01:05:52.553 --> 01:05:55.412
(laughter) which is important.

01:05:55.412 --> 01:05:58.550
It's amazing how many times
that question is not asked.

01:05:58.550 --> 01:06:00.478
We're definitely not doing damage
and everyone's more engaged,

01:06:00.478 --> 01:06:03.968
so even on that metric alone
it makes sense to move forward,

01:06:03.968 --> 01:06:06.490
but the more powerful thing is,
and everyone recognizes this,

01:06:06.490 --> 01:06:08.383
is that these kids are doing
trigonometry and algebra,

01:06:08.383 --> 01:06:12.095
that's not being measured on
the fifth grade assessment.

01:06:12.095 --> 01:06:13.863
I'm actually going to administer an SAT

01:06:13.863 --> 01:06:18.202
to a control fifth grade class
and to this fifth grade class

01:06:18.202 --> 01:06:19.505
and I'm hoping to see one thing.

01:06:19.505 --> 01:06:21.574
Obviously the fifth graders
who have been doing algebra

01:06:21.574 --> 01:06:24.469
will do much better on the
SAT, but I have a suspicion

01:06:24.469 --> 01:06:28.928
they'll do much better than the
average high school senior, too.

01:06:29.477 --> 01:06:32.251
I think if we do stuff like that and
then we can do more rigorous stuff.

01:06:32.251 --> 01:06:33.693
These aren't rigorous studies.

01:06:33.693 --> 01:06:35.895
This is me administering an SAT,

01:06:35.895 --> 01:06:38.758
but these will be the
data points that tell us.

01:06:38.758 --> 01:06:40.563
Then we can do a really rigorous study.

01:06:40.563 --> 01:06:42.237
Audience Member: One of
the obstacles you can hit

01:06:42.237 --> 01:06:43.969
is that those people that
went and got a master's degree

01:06:43.969 --> 01:06:45.606
so they could teach middle school math

01:06:45.606 --> 01:06:49.236
are going to be reluctant
to (unintelligible).

01:06:49.236 --> 01:06:51.523
Last comment before I turn it
over, if you make the effort

01:06:51.523 --> 01:06:54.641
to map your particular modules
to the Common Core standards,

01:06:54.641 --> 01:06:56.022
that would make it a lot -

01:06:56.022 --> 01:06:57.309
Sal: We are doing that as we speak.

01:06:57.309 --> 01:06:59.021
They're like 80% done.

01:06:59.021 --> 01:07:00.211
We're 80% done mapping.

01:07:00.211 --> 01:07:01.445
We have to actually
add a lot more modules.

01:07:01.445 --> 01:07:02.748
The videos are pretty comprehensive,

01:07:02.748 --> 01:07:05.417
but the modules we have to add a lot more.

01:07:05.417 --> 01:07:07.606
We're doing that, but it's
just a spreadsheet right now.

01:07:07.606 --> 01:07:10.089
We're going to surface that
so that you can navigate

01:07:10.089 --> 01:07:12.440
with the Common Core.

01:07:12.440 --> 01:07:14.825
To answer the teacher question,
this is the other thing,

01:07:14.825 --> 01:07:16.228
teachers can use this to stay -

01:07:16.228 --> 01:07:19.331
That's the other side effect,
teachers actually using this to learn.

01:07:19.331 --> 01:07:21.439
There have been studies
that show the best teachers

01:07:21.439 --> 01:07:23.169
are actually the ones who have -

01:07:23.169 --> 01:07:26.023
The best second grade math teachers
are the ones who know calculus,

01:07:26.023 --> 01:07:29.440
just because the kids know
that there's more there.

01:07:29.440 --> 01:07:30.690
They know what's going on.

01:07:30.690 --> 01:07:37.123
The teachers can use this to ramp
up and stay ahead of the curve.

01:07:38.346 --> 01:07:39.822
Audience Member: Well, speaking
of second grade teachers,

01:07:39.822 --> 01:07:41.740
I am one, so thank you.

01:07:41.740 --> 01:07:44.406
I want to say thank you to
LinkedIn for inviting me, as well.

01:07:44.406 --> 01:07:45.573
I'm from northern California.

01:07:45.573 --> 01:07:48.032
I teach at a charter
school and I actually have

01:07:48.032 --> 01:07:50.298
an employee here's son in my class.

01:07:50.298 --> 01:07:52.366
I had a question more about taking it back

01:07:52.366 --> 01:07:55.489
to the actual implementation.

01:07:55.489 --> 01:07:57.605
The Los Altos schools,
are they using a 1:1 ratio

01:07:57.605 --> 01:07:58.945
of computers in the classroom?

01:07:58.945 --> 01:07:59.777
Sal: Yes.

01:07:59.777 --> 01:08:01.068
Audience Member: Are
there kids at the computer

01:08:01.068 --> 01:08:02.445
doing that math lecture the whole time?

01:08:02.445 --> 01:08:05.401
Sal: They have 1:1, although what we found

01:08:05.401 --> 01:08:06.749
is you actually don't need 1:1,

01:08:06.749 --> 01:08:08.683
because so much of the time
is spent doing other things

01:08:08.683 --> 01:08:10.453
that you could probably
time share the computers.

01:08:10.453 --> 01:08:12.568
You could probably do a 3:1 ratio

01:08:12.568 --> 01:08:15.456
and it would probably
work out just as well,

01:08:15.456 --> 01:08:17.259
just because there's some time
where you're actually all working

01:08:17.259 --> 01:08:20.308
with your peers and you're
not even using the computer.

01:08:20.483 --> 01:08:22.507
That is a gaining factor.

01:08:22.507 --> 01:08:25.257
At some point, you do have to
have internet connectivity.

01:08:25.257 --> 01:08:28.572
We're thinking about offline use
cases for the developing world,

01:08:28.572 --> 01:08:32.505
but what we'd like to think
is, even when I went to school

01:08:32.505 --> 01:08:35.710
in the 80s and 90s in a
fairly middle of the road

01:08:35.710 --> 01:08:37.425
public school system in Louisiana,

01:08:37.425 --> 01:08:41.148
there were computers that
just went completely unused.

01:08:41.148 --> 01:08:43.174
I think the skepticism
for deploying more money

01:08:43.174 --> 01:08:45.387
behind computers is justified.

01:08:45.387 --> 01:08:48.491
It's like, "What are they doing
right now with the computers?

01:08:48.491 --> 01:08:50.425
"How is it actually helping anyone?"

01:08:50.425 --> 01:08:52.561
I think if you actually give
a use case for the computers

01:08:52.561 --> 01:08:54.697
and it's actually, now
that these people are -

01:08:54.697 --> 01:08:57.009
The teachers, the principals,
the administrators, the parents

01:08:57.009 --> 01:08:59.924
are getting this real-time data,
then I think the question becomes,

01:08:59.924 --> 01:09:01.902
"How can we operate
without these computers?"

01:09:01.902 --> 01:09:05.092
Then, there's a narrative here,
too, where at least I think

01:09:05.092 --> 01:09:07.768
you don't need textbooks anymore.

01:09:07.768 --> 01:09:09.137
That's a cost savings.

01:09:09.137 --> 01:09:13.953
Audience Member: Then implementing
it then multiple grade levels.

01:09:13.953 --> 01:09:15.354
With the modules you were talking about,

01:09:15.354 --> 01:09:16.743
I've started working through them myself,

01:09:16.743 --> 01:09:19.023
because I"m refreshing, trying
to get to the calculus level

01:09:19.023 --> 01:09:21.100
as a second grade teacher, I guess.

01:09:22.493 --> 01:09:25.598
Implementing it within fourth,
fifth, sixth, seventh, eighth,

01:09:25.598 --> 01:09:29.494
at what point are those kids,
because there's only so many modules,

01:09:29.494 --> 01:09:31.362
and if you're in school 186 days a year,

01:09:31.362 --> 01:09:35.700
how are they going to keep going
through all those modules (crosstalk)

01:09:35.700 --> 01:09:37.433
Sal: Some of these fifth
graders are almost done

01:09:37.433 --> 01:09:38.822
with all of our modules that we have,

01:09:38.822 --> 01:09:43.575
so we're ramping up, hiring faster
so we can stay ahead of them.

01:09:43.575 --> 01:09:47.117
The funny answer is, it's
funny that this is a problem.

01:09:47.883 --> 01:09:51.004
If I had a 12 year old or
13 year old that did that,

01:09:51.004 --> 01:09:52.612
I would say, "You know
what, just take the SAT,

01:09:52.612 --> 01:09:56.404
"take the GED, and go work
or something." (laughter)

01:09:56.404 --> 01:09:58.236
"Go explore things for a couple years

01:09:58.236 --> 01:09:59.817
and if you want to go to college, go to -

01:09:59.817 --> 01:10:01.287
That's a good problem.

01:10:01.287 --> 01:10:04.651
It's funny, it sounds like a crazy
idea, but someone recommended

01:10:04.651 --> 01:10:08.263
that we should start
schools where it isn't

01:10:08.263 --> 01:10:11.098
this is the tuition per month or
this is tuition for a semester,

01:10:11.098 --> 01:10:15.569
it's just like if your kid gets
over 700 on the SAT, you pay us -

01:10:15.569 --> 01:10:18.270
Right now, if you go to a
private school, $30,000 a year

01:10:18.270 --> 01:10:21.487
for 12 years is $360,000, right?

01:10:21.487 --> 01:10:24.485
Most of them are still not
getting 700s on the SAT, right?

01:10:24.485 --> 01:10:27.235
So you say, however long it
takes, if it takes them a week,

01:10:27.235 --> 01:10:29.984
if it takes them 20 years,
if your kid gets a 700 -

01:10:29.984 --> 01:10:32.986
We'll educate them, if your kid
gets a 700, pay us 100 grand.

01:10:32.986 --> 01:10:37.652
It was a joke, but that
actually would be good,

01:10:37.652 --> 01:10:40.235
because if the kid finishes
faster, it's good for everyone.

01:10:40.235 --> 01:10:42.319
It's good for the kid, it's
good for the school system,

01:10:42.319 --> 01:10:45.210
it's good for resource allocation.

01:10:45.210 --> 01:10:47.644
I know this is being taped, so
don't take my idea seriously

01:10:47.644 --> 01:10:49.375
about this performance, but actually -

01:10:49.375 --> 01:10:54.179
Anyway, (laughter) the simple
answer is it's not a problem.

01:10:54.179 --> 01:10:55.380
It's an awesome problem.

01:10:55.380 --> 01:10:57.317
Actually, the best thing
to do with that kid is,

01:10:57.317 --> 01:11:00.927
the kid who's already maxed
out everything, make him a TA.

01:11:00.927 --> 01:11:03.648
Audience Member: Yeah, I'm
just seeing the balance between

01:11:03.648 --> 01:11:06.178
language development,
writing, reading (crosstalk)

01:11:06.178 --> 01:11:08.510
all that other stuff, so you have
a sixth, seventh, eighth grader

01:11:08.510 --> 01:11:10.762
who has maxed out your
modules in calculus,

01:11:10.762 --> 01:11:13.096
but they're not prepared
yet, in my opinion

01:11:13.096 --> 01:11:18.042
to go out to the work field, in terms
of their writing ability (crosstalk)

01:11:18.042 --> 01:11:19.435
Sal: There's two things here.

01:11:19.435 --> 01:11:20.736
One is because these
are fifth grade classes,

01:11:20.736 --> 01:11:22.768
the same teacher does
teach all the subjects.

01:11:22.768 --> 01:11:25.624
One, these teachers are frustrated
with the other subjects now,

01:11:25.624 --> 01:11:27.342
because they feel like
it's like stone ages now,

01:11:27.342 --> 01:11:29.411
because they don't have this data
analytic, self-paced teaching.

01:11:29.411 --> 01:11:33.081
Hopefully we can expand and build
some tools into the other subjects.

01:11:33.081 --> 01:11:35.649
The other thing is we've
even thought maybe we should

01:11:35.649 --> 01:11:36.874
start one school ourselves.

01:11:36.874 --> 01:11:39.542
We actually even thought about
doing it someplace around here,

01:11:39.542 --> 01:11:42.542
so maybe you would have
an option other than ...

01:11:42.542 --> 01:11:47.875
It's not by grade level,
it's just one room classroom.

01:11:47.875 --> 01:11:49.209
In the same room you have Kindergartners,

01:11:49.209 --> 01:11:51.709
in the same room you have 18 year olds

01:11:51.709 --> 01:11:54.670
and the stuff that you already
have maxed out, you are a TA

01:11:54.670 --> 01:11:56.791
and the other stuff you are being TA-ed.

01:11:56.791 --> 01:11:59.339
I think if you do a model
like that, I think it's -

01:11:59.339 --> 01:12:00.792
There's all sorts of interesting models

01:12:00.792 --> 01:12:02.624
about teaching each other and maturity

01:12:02.624 --> 01:12:04.708
that you can only get in
that type of a framework.

01:12:04.708 --> 01:12:07.982
Right now, you're stuck with
just your other ten year olds.

01:12:07.982 --> 01:12:08.919
We've all seen it.

01:12:08.919 --> 01:12:11.042
If you have older kids
around, you act more mature

01:12:11.042 --> 01:12:13.154
and if you have younger kids
around, you act more mature,

01:12:13.154 --> 01:12:15.426
because you have responsibility now.

01:12:15.426 --> 01:12:17.191
I think if we explore
that a little bit more,

01:12:17.191 --> 01:12:20.043
we'll have a way that we can really -

01:12:20.043 --> 01:12:22.264
Once a kid is giving more into the system

01:12:22.264 --> 01:12:24.287
than they're taking out, pay them.

01:12:24.287 --> 01:12:26.402
They should be TAs.

01:12:26.402 --> 01:12:27.619
Audience Member: As a
teacher, thank you, Sal.

01:12:27.619 --> 01:12:29.817
Sal: Oh yeah, thanks, yeah.

01:12:30.574 --> 01:12:34.317
Jeff: Speaking of thanks, it's
interesting juxtaposition.

01:12:34.317 --> 01:12:37.521
At our last In day, we
do this once a month,

01:12:37.521 --> 01:12:39.358
where employees have an opportunity

01:12:39.358 --> 01:12:41.359
to invest time and energy in the things

01:12:41.359 --> 01:12:43.649
they're most inspired by and excited by.

01:12:43.649 --> 01:12:46.983
Education's a recurring theme
for us, reinventing education.

01:12:46.983 --> 01:12:51.734
At the last In day, we
screened Waiting for Superman.

01:12:51.734 --> 01:12:53.400
I think a lot of people
in the room today saw it

01:12:53.400 --> 01:12:56.234
and it's hard not to
walk away from the film

01:12:56.234 --> 01:12:59.042
feeling a bit of despair.

01:12:59.042 --> 01:13:02.816
I think there is an understanding
of things need to improve,

01:13:02.816 --> 01:13:05.984
but I also think, perhaps
naively, prior to seeing the film,

01:13:05.984 --> 01:13:09.131
a lot folks believe that
if you live in this country

01:13:09.131 --> 01:13:13.523
and you wanted to be
educated, you wanted to learn

01:13:13.523 --> 01:13:16.528
and do your best and be prepared
for opportunity when it came,

01:13:16.528 --> 01:13:20.263
that you could and what
that movie certainly shed

01:13:20.263 --> 01:13:27.037
a very, very dark light on was
the fact that that's not the case,

01:13:27.037 --> 01:13:29.508
that it's come down to a lottery

01:13:29.508 --> 01:13:32.341
and I think most folks
here learned the economics

01:13:32.341 --> 01:13:34.818
of lotteries at a very young age.

01:13:34.818 --> 01:13:37.681
If we all believe that
the future of our country,

01:13:37.681 --> 01:13:40.067
to a large extent, depends
on the next generation

01:13:40.067 --> 01:13:41.720
and their ability to be educated,

01:13:41.720 --> 01:13:44.219
we don't want to be
placing a bet on a lottery,

01:13:44.219 --> 01:13:47.123
we want to be placing a
bet on people like you.

01:13:47.123 --> 01:13:51.485
As depressing as some
of those themes were,

01:13:51.485 --> 01:13:54.989
I think you represent the exact opposite.

01:13:55.436 --> 01:13:58.726
You represent the fact
that what could appear

01:13:58.726 --> 01:14:02.537
as completely intractable,
unsolveable problems

01:14:02.537 --> 01:14:06.469
are absolutely solvable
and you and I think

01:14:06.469 --> 01:14:09.041
you mentioned eight or nine folks,

01:14:09.041 --> 01:14:11.939
one of the key things we
like to talk about here

01:14:11.939 --> 01:14:15.705
is how to scale and how
to transform things.

01:14:15.705 --> 01:14:18.371
You are living proof of
what's possible when someone

01:14:18.371 --> 01:14:21.316
with incredible vision,
intelligence, and energy

01:14:21.316 --> 01:14:23.871
channels that into something -

01:14:23.871 --> 01:14:26.488
Sal: Looks (laughter)

01:14:26.488 --> 01:14:29.729
Jeff: Sure. (crosstalk)

01:14:29.729 --> 01:14:35.122
Channels that into something so
extraordinarily important and valuable.

01:14:35.122 --> 01:14:39.233
On behalf of all of us, Sal,
thank you for everything

01:14:39.233 --> 01:14:44.314
you and your team are doing
to reinvent education.

01:14:44.907 --> 01:14:46.882
I know I speak for all of us
when I say we're going to do

01:14:46.882 --> 01:14:48.716
everything within our power to help you.

01:14:48.716 --> 01:14:52.716
Sal: Awesome, yeah, that's
exciting. (applause)

